    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "that makes sense. can u show me a quick example? like how i'd swap out my list comp for a generator specifically when i'm iterating through rows in a dataframe? also is there anything else that typically causes these sudden spikes in memory usage besides just storing too much in a list?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Here's a quick example of swapping a list comprehension for a generator when iterating through a DataFrame. Instead of building a full list, you use a generator expression within a loop or when feeding data to another function.\n\nFor instance, if you were filtering and transforming rows:\n\n**List Comprehension (Memory Hog):**\n```python\n# This builds the entire new list in memory immediately!\nnew_data = [process_row(row) for index, row in df.iterrows()]\n```\n\n**Generator Expression (Memory Saver):**\n```python\n# This creates an iterator that yields results one by one.\ndata_generator = (process_row(row) for index, row in df.iterrows())\n\n# Now you iterate over the generator, processing one item at a time.\nfor result in data_generator:\n    # Do something with the result immediately, don't store it all!\n    print(result)\n```\n\nAnother common culprit for sudden memory spikes, besides hoarding lists, is loading the entire DataFrame into memory in the first place, especially if it's huge. Also, be careful with intermediate data structures you create inside your loop.",
      "source": "target",
